oral order. Opera performance blurred lines between public and private life, and offered a stage on which to act out gender and class transgressions. This work illuminates how the state and various urban constituencies manipulated opera to their own ends, and sheds light on empire-wide transformations underway at the time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aOperas, ChinesexPolitical aspectszChinazBeijing. 0aOperas, ChinesexSocial aspectszChinazBeijing. 0aOperas, ChinesezChinazBeijingxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804782623zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804782623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804782623.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles